The Geolocation API is used to access the user's current location. Since this can compromise privacy, the location is not available unless the user approves it.

**Browser Support:**
The Geolocation API is supported in all modern browsers.

**Using the Geolocation API:**
The Geolocation API is accessed via a call to navigator.geolocation. This will cause the browser to ask the user for permission to access their location data.

```javascript
navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(showPosition);
```

**Complete Example:**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
<p>Click the button to get your coordinates.</p>
<button onclick="getLocation()">Try It</button>
<p id="demo"></p>

<script>
const x = document.getElementById("demo");

function getLocation() {
  if (navigator.geolocation) {
    navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(showPosition);
  } else {
    x.innerHTML = "Geolocation is not supported by this browser.";
  }
}

function showPosition(position) {
  x.innerHTML = "Latitude: " + position.coords.latitude + 
  "<br>Longitude: " + position.coords.longitude;
}
</script>
</body>
</html>
```

**Error Handling:**
The second parameter of getCurrentPosition() is used to handle errors.
```javascript
function showError(error) {
  switch(error.code) {
    case error.PERMISSION_DENIED:
      x.innerHTML = "User denied the request for Geolocation."
      break;
    case error.POSITION_UNAVAILABLE:
      x.innerHTML = "Location information is unavailable."
      break;
    case error.TIMEOUT:
      x.innerHTML = "The request to get user location timed out."
      break;
    default:
      x.innerHTML = "An unknown error occurred."
  }
}
```

**Important Notes:**
- Geolocation only works on secure contexts (HTTPS)
- Most accurate for devices with GPS (smartphones)
- User must grant permission
- Privacy-sensitive feature

Drag and drop is a very common feature. It is when you "grab" an object and drag it to a different location. HTML5 has a native Drag and Drop API that makes this easy to implement.

**Make an Element Draggable:**
First, to make an element draggable, set the draggable attribute to true:
```html
<img draggable="true" id="drag1" src="img_logo.gif">
```

**What to Drag - ondragstart and setData():**
Specify what should happen when the element is dragged. The dataTransfer.setData() method sets the data type and the value of the dragged data.
```html
define drag(ev) {
  ev.dataTransfer.setData("text", ev.target.id);
}
```

**Where to Drop - ondragover:**
By default, data/elements cannot be dropped in other elements. To allow a drop, we must prevent the default handling of the element using preventDefault().
```html
define allowDrop(ev) {
  ev.preventDefault();
}
```

**Do the Drop - ondrop:**
When the dragged data is dropped, a drop event occurs. Use dataTransfer.getData() to get the dragged data.
```html
define drop(ev) {
  ev.preventDefault();
  var data = ev.dataTransfer.getData("text");
  ev.target.appendChild(document.getElementById(data));
}
```

**Complete Example:**
```html
<!DOCTYPE HTML>
<html>
<head>
<style>
#div1 {width:350px;height:70px;padding:10px;border:1px solid #aaaaaa;}
</style>
<script>
function allowDrop(ev) {
  ev.preventDefault();
}

function drag(ev) {
  ev.dataTransfer.setData("text", ev.target.id);
}

function drop(ev) {
  ev.preventDefault();
  var data = ev.dataTransfer.getData("text");
  ev.target.appendChild(document.getElementById(data));
}
</script>
</head>
<body>

<p>Drag the W3Schools image into the rectangle:</p>

<div id="div1" ondrop="drop(event)" ondragover="allowDrop(event)"></div>
<br>
<img id="drag1" src="img_logo.gif" draggable="true" ondragstart="drag(event)" width="336" height="69">

</body>
</html>
```

**Key Events:**
- `dragstart` - When dragging starts
- `drag` - While dragging
- `dragend` - When dragging ends
- `dragenter` - When dragged element enters drop zone
- `dragover` - While over drop zone
- `dragleave` - When leaving drop zone
- `drop` - When dropped

With web storage, applications can store data locally within the user's browser. Before HTML5, application data had to be stored in cookies, included in every server request. Web storage is more secure, and large amounts of data can be stored locally.

**What is HTML Web Storage?**
- More secure than cookies
- Large amounts of data can be stored (at least 5MB)
- Information is never transferred to the server
- Per origin (per domain and protocol)

**Web Storage Objects:**
- **localStorage** - Stores data with no expiration date (data not lost when browser is closed)
- **sessionStorage** - Stores data for one session (data lost when browser tab is closed)

**The localStorage Object:**
```html
<script>
// Store data
localStorage.setItem("lastname", "Smith");

// Retrieve data
document.getElementById("result").innerHTML = localStorage.getItem("lastname");
</script>
```

**Example: Counting Clicks:**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>

<p><button onclick="clickCounter()" type="button">Click me!</button></p>
<div id="result"></div>

<script>
function clickCounter() {
  if (typeof(Storage) !== "undefined") {
    if (localStorage.clickcount) {
      localStorage.clickcount = Number(localStorage.clickcount) + 1;
    } else {
      localStorage.clickcount = 1;
    }
    document.getElementById("result").innerHTML = "You have clicked the button " + localStorage.clickcount + " time(s).";
  } else {
    document.getElementById("result").innerHTML = "Sorry, your browser does not support web storage...";
  }
}
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

**The sessionStorage Object:**
```html
<script>
if (sessionStorage.clickcount) {
  sessionStorage.clickcount = Number(sessionStorage.clickcount) + 1;
} else {
  sessionStorage.clickcount = 1;
}
document.getElementById("result").innerHTML = "You have clicked the button " + sessionStorage.clickcount + " time(s) in this session.";
</script>
```

**Common Methods:**
- `setItem(key, value)` - Store data
- `getItem(key)` - Retrieve data
- `removeItem(key)` - Remove specific item
- `clear()` - Clear all data
- `key(index)` - Get key at index

**When to Use:**
- localStorage: User preferences, shopping cart, theme settings
- sessionStorage: Form data during multi-step process, temporary session data

Before smartphones, every website was designed for desktop screens. When the iPhone launched in 2007, it tried to fit full desktop websites onto a tiny 320px screen by zooming out. That made everything tiny and unreadable. The meta viewport tag fixed this by telling mobile browsers: "Scale my page properly for this screen size."

**The magic tag (always include it):**
```html
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
```

**What each part does:**
- `width=device-width` — Sets the page width to match the device's screen width (not zoomed-out desktop width).
- `initial-scale=1.0` — Sets the initial zoom level to 100% (not zoomed out or in).

**Without this tag (bad):**
```html
<!-- Browsers assume 980px desktop width on a 375px phone → everything is tiny -->
```
User sees: An entire desktop website squished into a small phone screen. Text is unreadable, buttons are tiny. The user must pinch and zoom constantly.

**With this tag (good):**
```html
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
```
User sees: Content that fills the phone screen. Text is readable, buttons are tappable. No pinching needed.

**Additional viewport settings:**
```html
<!-- Prevent zooming (usually NOT recommended - hurts accessibility) -->
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0, user-scalable=no">

<!-- Set maximum zoom level -->
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0, maximum-scale=2.0">
```
**Warning:** Avoid `user-scalable=no` unless you have a very good reason. It blocks users with visual impairments from zooming your page.

**How viewport works with CSS media queries:**
The viewport tag enables CSS media queries to work correctly. Media queries apply different styles based on screen width.

```css
/* Default: desktop styles */
.container {
  display: flex;
  gap: 20px;
}

/* Tablet screens (768px to 1024px) */
@media (max-width: 1024px) {
  .container {
    gap: 15px;
  }
}

/* Mobile screens (below 768px) */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .container {
    flex-direction: column; /* Stack vertically on phones */
    gap: 10px;
  }
}
```

**Testing responsive design:**
1. In Chrome: Right-click → Inspect → Click the "Toggle device toolbar" icon (phone/tablet icon).
2. Select different devices (iPhone, Pixel, iPad) from the dropdown.
3. Resize your browser window manually to see how the layout changes.

**Common responsive patterns:**
- **Stacking:** Columns stack vertically on mobile instead of sitting side-by-side.
- **Hamburger menu:** Navigation links hide behind a ☰ icon on mobile.
- **Larger touch targets:** Buttons are at least 44x44px on mobile for fingers.
- **Readable font sizes:** Minimum 16px for body text on mobile.

**Complete responsive example:**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Responsive Page</title>
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: system-ui, sans-serif;
      margin: 0;
      padding: 20px;
    }
    .cards {
      display: flex;
      gap: 20px;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
    }
    .card {
      background: #f5f5f5;
      padding: 20px;
      border-radius: 8px;
      flex: 1;
      min-width: 200px;
    }
    /* Mobile: cards stack, font gets smaller */
    @media (max-width: 640px) {
      body {
        padding: 10px;
      }
      .cards {
        flex-direction: column;
      }
      h1 {
        font-size: 1.5rem;
      }
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Responsive Card Layout</h1>
  <div class="cards">
    <div class="card">Card 1</div>
    <div class="card">Card 2</div>
    <div class="card">Card 3</div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
```

Remember: Adding the meta viewport tag is the single most important step for mobile-friendly websites. Without it, even the most beautiful responsive CSS will not work correctly on phones.
